<subSubSection pageNumber="930" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="930">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="930">Note:</emphasis>
There has been some confusion between this name and 
<taxonomicName authority="L. However, Stauffer" authorityName="L. However, Stauffer" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Phyllanthaceae" genus="Phyllanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="epiphyllanthus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="930">Phyllanthus epiphyllanthus</emphasis>
L. However, Stauffer
</taxonomicName>
(in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="930">
Mitt. Bot. Mus. Univ. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Zürich">Zuerich</normalizedToken>
</emphasis>
213: 221. 1959) provided a detailed treatment, and concluded that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Endl." baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1771" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Santalaceae" genus="Exocarpos" kingdom="Plantae" order="Santalales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="longifolius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="930">E. longifolius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the correct name for this taxon. He (p. 222) indicated Rumphius, Herb. Amboin. 7: t. 12 as the type, and also indicated a 
<typeStatus>neotype</typeStatus>
from New Guinea. The Rumphius plate is original material for the name and is accepted as the 
<typeStatus>lectotype</typeStatus>
, with 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Stauffer’s">Stauffer's</normalizedToken>
<typeStatus>neotype</typeStatus>
interpreted as an 
<typeStatus>epitype</typeStatus>
under Art. 9.8.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
